<Layout title={guideData.title} description={guideData.description}>
  <!-- FAQ Structured Data -->
  <StructuredData
    type="FAQPage"
    data={[
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the best AI website builder for real estate?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "For independent real estate agents, Mixo ($9/month) is the best choice with affordable pricing, lead capture forms, property showcase capabilities, and easy agent profile setup. Squarespace works well for brokerages wanting professional credibility, agent profiles, and consistent brand presentation across multiple agents. Framer is ideal for luxury agents and high-end properties wanting stunning designs (9.5/10) and modern aesthetic that impresses affluent buyers. Wix offers good features for property managers needing booking systems and contact forms. Durable offers fastest setup (30 seconds) for quick agent websites. For most real estate professionals, prioritize: property photo galleries, lead capture forms, mobile optimization (critical for buyers browsing on phones), agent profile/bio, and clear contact information."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can real estate agents use AI website builders?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, AI website builders work excellently for real estate agents. Modern AI builders create professional agent websites with property showcases, lead capture forms, agent profiles, and contact information. However, most AI builders do NOT directly integrate with MLS databases for automatic property syncing. For MLS integration, you typically need: real estate-specific platforms (Zillow, Realtor.com), WordPress with IDX plugins, or custom development. AI builders are perfect for: agent profiles and personal branding, showcasing sold and current properties manually, lead capture for buyer and seller inquiries, neighborhood expertise display, testimonials and success stories, contact forms and scheduling. For most independent agents, AI builders provide better branding, design quality, and lead generation than template real estate platforms."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Do AI builders integrate with MLS for property listings?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Most AI website builders do NOT directly integrate with MLS (Multiple Listing Service) databases. MLS integration typically requires: real estate-specific platforms (Zillow, Realtor.com, MLS vendor websites), WordPress with IDX/MLS plugins, or custom development with API access. However, AI builders work excellently for: manual property listings with photos and details, single property websites for luxury listings, agent profiles and personal branding, lead capture forms and inquiry management, neighborhood showcases and area expertise, sold property success stories. For most independent agents with 5-20 active listings, manual updates on AI builders provide better control, customization, and branding than automated MLS feeds. Only larger brokerages with 50+ listings need automated MLS syncing."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What features should real estate websites include?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Real estate websites need these key features: Professional agent photo and bio prominently displayed (clients hire agents, not websites), property listings with high-quality photos and details (beds, baths, price, address), lead capture forms above fold for inquiries (73% of buyers come from web forms), active search areas or neighborhoods you serve, sold properties or success stories for social proof, client testimonials and reviews with photos, clear contact information (phone, email, social links), property search or filtering if you have multiple listings, video tour embeds for properties (YouTube, Vimeo), mobile optimization (79% of buyers browse on phones). For luxury agents: virtual tours, high-end photography showcase, neighborhood guides, market statistics, home valuation landing pages. Your website should build trust, showcase your expertise, and make it incredibly easy for potential clients to contact you."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much should real estate agents spend on a website?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Real estate website spending by agent type: New agents or part-time agents: Mixo ($9/month) or Carrd ($19-49/year) for basic presence. Independent agents: Squarespace ($23/month) or Framer ($15/month) for professional appearance. Luxury agents: Framer ($15-35/month) for stunning designs that impress affluent clients. Brokerages with multiple agents: Squarespace ($23-65/month) or Webflow ($23-59/month) for custom branding. Property managers: Wix ($16-45/month) for booking features and contact forms. Budget rule: Spend 1-2% of expected annual commission on your website. If you expect $100K in commissions, budget $1-2K annually ($83-166/month). Your website generates leads that close into deals - it's an investment, not an expense. Professional photography ($200-500 per listing) delivers higher ROI than premium website platforms. Focus on: high-quality photos, mobile optimization, easy lead capture, clear contact information more than expensive website subscriptions."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Which builder is best for different real estate professionals?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Different real estate professionals have different website needs: Independent agents: Mixo ($9/month) for affordable lead capture and property showcases, Squarespace ($23/month) for professional credibility, Framer ($15/month) for modern design-forward presentation. Luxury agents: Framer ($15-35/month) for stunning 9.5/10 designs that impress affluent buyers, Webflow ($23-59/month) for complete customization of high-end presentations. Property managers: Wix ($16-45/month) for booking systems and contact forms, Squarespace ($23/month) for polished property displays. Brokerages: Squarespace ($23-65/month) for consistent brand presentation across multiple agents with agent profile pages, Webflow ($23-59/month) for complete custom control of brokerage branding. New agents: Durable ($12-20/month) for fastest 30-second setup to get started quickly, Carrd ($19-49/year) for budget one-page presence. Solo practitioners: Mixo for affordability, Squarespace for professionalism, Framer for design impact."
        }
      },
